<section id="lipid-cholesterol">
    <h2>Lipid & Cholesterol Experts</h2>
    <p>Specialists in lipidology offering nuanced perspectives on cholesterol's role in heart disease - a topic with significant ongoing debate.</p>

    <div class="expert-card">
        <h3>Dr. Thomas Dayspring, MD, FACP, FNLA</h3>
        <p class="credentials"><strong>Credentials:</strong> Clinical Lipidologist | Fellow, National Lipid Association | 40+ years clinical experience</p>
        <p class="focus"><strong>Focus:</strong> Advanced lipid testing; LDL particle number vs. LDL cholesterol; apoB as superior marker</p>
        <div class="expert-perspective">
            <h4>Key Perspective</h4>
            <blockquote>
                "LDL cholesterol is a flawed metric. What actually matters is the number of LDL particles (LDL-P) or apoB. Two people with identical LDL-C can have dramatically different particle counts - and dramatically different risks. We need to stop treating a number and start understanding the actual pathophysiology."
            </blockquote>
        </div>
        <p class="contributions"><strong>Notable Contributions:</strong> Educating physicians on advanced lipid testing; explaining discordance between LDL-C and LDL-P</p>
    </div>

    <div class="expert-card">
        <h3>Dr. Ronald Krauss, MD</h3>
        <p class="credentials"><strong>Credentials:</strong> Senior Scientist, Children's Hospital Oakland Research Institute | Professor, UCSF | Pioneer of LDL subclass research</p>
        <p class="focus"><strong>Focus:</strong> LDL particle subclasses; dietary effects on lipoprotein metabolism; precision medicine in lipidology</p>
        <div class="expert-perspective">
            <h4>Key Perspective</h4>
            <blockquote>
                "Small, dense LDL particles are more atherogenic than large, buoyant LDL. Diet dramatically affects which type you produce. A low-fat, high-carb diet often shifts the pattern toward smaller, more dangerous particles - the opposite of what we intended."
            </blockquote>
        </div>
        <p class="contributions"><strong>Notable Contributions:</strong> Discovering LDL subclass patterns; research showing saturated fat doesn't necessarily increase heart disease risk; nuancing the cholesterol hypothesis</p>
    </div>

    <div class="expert-card">
        <h3><a href="/experts/peter-attia">Dr. Peter Attia, MD</a></h3>
        <p class="credentials"><strong>Credentials:</strong> Physician | Founder of Early Medical | Host of "The Drive" podcast | Former surgical oncologist</p>
